Plots with team logos

NFL

Package used:

  • nflplotR. This packages works with ggplot to create plots with NFL team logos. Here’s a great resource for Getting started with nflplotR

Installing nflplotR:

install.packages("nflplotR")

Then loading it into your session:

library(nflplotR)

The key to successfully loading NFL team logos to your plots is this: The data frame you build your plot from should contain a team abbreviation column, and these team abbreviations must match with the team abbreviations used in the nflplotR package.

The team abbreviations in nflfastR match perfectly!

Here’s the example we went through in class, that ends with team expected points added season totals for both offense and defense, from the nflfastR package

library(nflfastR)

nfl <- load_pbp(seasons = 2024)
#loads 2024 season play by play

df <- nfl |> 
  filter(season_type == 'REG', play_type != 'no_play')
# filters out no plays, and considers only the regular season

offense <- df |>
  filter(play_type %in% c('run','pass')) |> 
  group_by(team = posteam) |>
  summarise(off_epa = mean(epa))
# creates team average epa for all the team's offensive plays, for each team

defense <- df |>
  filter(play_type %in% c('run','pass')) |>
  group_by(team = defteam) |>
  summarise(def_epa = mean(epa, na.rm = TRUE))
# creates team average epa for all team's defensive plays, for each team

team_epa <- inner_join(offense, defense, by = "team") 
# joins the two data frames into a single data frame

Reproduce the code above, and check that your data frame looks like this (notice the team abbreviations :)):

Here’s a fancy plot of these data (based on a plot in the getting started link above) using a team logos for points, a reversed y-axis scale so that higher up the axis corresponds to better defensive performance, and other layers to improve how easily the plot communicates information

library(nflplotR)
ggplot(team_epa, aes(x = off_epa, y = def_epa))+
  geom_point()+
  scale_y_reverse()+
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = c(.4, .3, .2, .1, 0, -.1, -.2, -.3), alpha = .2)+
  geom_mean_lines(aes(y0 = off_epa, x0 = def_epa)) + 
  labs(
    x = "Offense EPA/play",
    y = "Defense EPA/play",
    caption = "Data from nflfastR",
    title = "2024 NFL Offensive and Defensive EPA per Play"
  ) + 
  geom_nfl_logos(aes(team_abbr = team), width = 0.07, alpha = .7) +
  theme_bw()

MLB

Package used:

  • mlbplotR. This packages works with ggplot to create plots with NFL team logos. Here’s a great resource for Getting started with mlbplotR

Installing mlbplotR:

install.packages("mlbplotR")

We check the team abbreviations used in the mlbplotR package

team_abbr <- mlbplotR::valid_team_names()
team_abbr
##  [1] "AL"  "ATL" "AZ"  "BAL" "BOS" "CHC" "CIN" "CLE" "COL" "CWS" "DET" "HOU"
## [13] "KC"  "LAA" "LAD" "MIA" "MIL" "MIN" "MLB" "NL"  "NYM" "NYY" "OAK" "PHI"
## [25] "PIT" "SD"  "SEA" "SF"  "STL" "TB"  "TEX" "TOR" "WSH"

These are different than the abbreviations used in the Lahman data, so we can plot team data from Lahman with logos if we create a new team abbreviation column.

The code below does this by ‘brute force’:

library(Lahman)

pit23 <- Pitching |> 
  filter(yearID == 2023) |> 
  group_by(teamID) |> 
  summarize(HR_pit = sum(HR))
# this creates a df of total HR given up each team in 2023

hit23 <- Batting |> 
  filter(yearID == 2023) |> 
  group_by(teamID) |> 
  summarize(HR_hit = sum(HR))
# this creates a df of total HR hit by each team in 2023

team_HR <- inner_join(pit23,hit23,by='teamID')
# this joins the two data frames.

# note, the teamID column in Lahman uses different abbreviations than the ones printed above.

# we create a new teams data frame to use as a map for assigning the correct team abbreviation for any Lahman data for which we want to use team logos.

teams <- data.frame(teamID = team_HR$teamID, team = c('AZ','ATL','BAL','BOS','CHW','CHC','CIN','CLE','COL','DET','HOU','KC','LAA','LAD','MIA','MIL','MIN','NYY','NYM','OAK','PHI','PIT','SD','SEA','SF','STL','TB','TEX','TOR','WSH'))

# Then we add the correct abbreviations to our team_HR data frame:

team_HR <- left_join(team_HR,teams,by='teamID')

# Note, we indicate the correct team_abbr in an aesthetic within the geom_mlb_logos() layer
ggplot(team_HR,aes(x = HR_hit,y = HR_pit)) + 
  geom_point()+
  geom_mlb_logos(aes(team_abbr = team), width = 0.05, alpha = 0.7)+
  scale_y_reverse()

NBA

Package: - nbaplotR Resource

Installing the package. The resource above recommends (which worked for me):

if (!require("pak")) install.packages("pak")
pak::pak("mrcaseb/nbaplotR")

Here are the valid team abbreviations for NBA teams:

nbaplotR::valid_team_names()

In the data set below, scraped from basketball reference, the team abbreviation column was added manually, so that logos could be added to plots.

Notice, in the plots above, actual points lurk behind the logos. We can eliminate the points if we omit the geom_point() layer

nba <- read.csv('~/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-LinfieldUniversity/Spring 25/DATA 299/presentations/linear models/csv/nba24_teams.csv')

library(nbaplotR)

ggplot(nba,aes(x = EFG_o, y = EFG_d,label = Team))+
# geom_point() + 
  geom_nba_logos(aes(team_abbr = Team_abr, width = 0.05))+
  scale_y_reverse()+
  theme_bw()
